The proposals are, in a word, embarrassingly bad. The vagueness on implementation and the implicit assumptions that underlie the proposals' justifications (that renewable energy can replace the entirety of US electricity generation, that the richest taxpayers don't pay their fair share, that the federal government even has any business dealing with most of these questions - building code is a local issue, for one) make it clear this is a politically biased venture and not at all serious about consensus building.
What would you change to make you recons:
The only possible alternative energy source to fossil fuels is nuclear.  Wind and solar are vanity projects to demonstrate commitment to environmentalism, not a serious alternative to fossil fuel-based electricity generation.
The highest earners in the country already pay far more than their fair share of taxes.  Reduce out-of-control spending on entitlements and defense to eliminate the deficit.  Emphasis on entitlements.
Government interference in healthcare is at least half the problem.  Allow doctors to order the tests they think are necessary per patient instead of thinking some bureaucrat in Washington or do-gooder think tank knows better.  Unions are massively unpopular nowadays; they are essentially money laundering machines for the Democrat Party, and half the problems with constructing low-income housing are union-related.  The other half is local government, and the feds cannot and should not interfere there.  Giving poor people more money is unpopular to everyone but poor people.  Throwing money at research does not guarantee innovation, but it does incentivize fraud.  Look at private venture capital firms.  Rural areas need internet infrastructure.  Urban areas, regardless of how low-income, have more than adequate internet access.  Your proposals are so vague as to be meaningless or duplicate existing efforts.  *How* will you incentivize worker training or public health programs to reduce obesity?  Federal subsidies?  Tax credits?  You can't force people to do things they don't want to do.  Everyone already knows obesity and smoking are bad for you.  Anyone who's still smoking or still fat is so by choice.  It's easy to get people to agree to 'make everything better.'  The problems come from *implementation.*  Most of these proposals do not offer a hint as to how the goal will be reached, and do not seem to take into account the law of unintended consequences.

What would you change to make you recons: A lot of this sounds like you don’t understand the reasons behind the problems Americans experience. We need a high, livable minimum wage (regardless of tips). That is simply a necessity. We need true universal single-payer healthcare—none of this “incentivize people to be/eat healthy” BS. To anyone not with actual health problems and not just a couple pounds they want to lose that is insulting. I should salad myself out of thyroid cancer? Adrenal insufficiency? Come on. Even if we are focusing on weight, which is a terrible measure of health when you start to look into it, people’s behaviors are almost always tied to their circumstances and those circumstances are usually not mostly under people’s control. Food deserts, stress, horrifically poor work-life balance, low wages, high cost of living, poor to nonexistent healthcare,  and the inability to access affordable medications that people’s doctors think are best for them all contribute more to the purported “obesity epidemic” or “health epidemic” than any individual’s choices do. For education: fund true education, which takes time, care and may not look efficient. Encourage schools or teachers to not “teach to the test” perhaps by changing how we fund schools and education. I don’t actually hate all of your individual proposals, but the way you described them en masse was tone deaf and indicates lack of understanding. On teachers pay based on “effectiveness”: I don’t think that effectiveness of teaching, however that might be judged—presumably by students’ test results?—is what should determine teacher pay. Firstly, teachers work with what their students bring to the table. A lot of times that is fear, hunger, and an understanding that for the majority of US citizens, upwards social mobility is not likely, and not because of individuals’ actions. Under these circumstances students often don’t learn as well or try as hard. The teachers will therefore not be judged to be “effective”, and we will underpay our hardest working teachers. Those who often give the most. However, if the teacher is in a rich district where their students are well fed, have tutors, come from families with some extra money, etc? The teachers will seem more “effective”. Furthermore, even two teachers who work with the same student population can have different immediate effects because they’re teaching differently but both can still have huge value to students. One might seem less effective but actually be teaching something that takes a long time to acquire and put into practice. That might not show up on tests or not show up fast enough to correctly improve the teacher’s “score”. On “Efficient Energy Regulations”: I don’t believe that inefficient necessarily means “unnecessary” or “not valuable”, so I don’t trust this statement to do the best thing for the climate or humans. I do support your propositions to reduce methane and cost of carbon emissions. I also think that the carbon credit trading scheme is bad. I don’t know about the carbon border tariff though. Tariffs are usually a bad idea, and I do think we should support the world’s developing economies, especially since the US has meddled in their politics in the past (School of the Americas, anyone?) I do NOT support charter schools. I do support increasing money for under resourced schools, but I want more resources for the students and their families, universal school meals, more than just throwing money at the problem willy-nilly. I do not support raising the retirement age. I don’t even know my feelings on a lot of the tax stuff that appeared in my “good idea” area. There is also something that just says “Federal Spending & Debt Overall Proposal” in Not Sure. What even is that? How should I know if I support or not? Your methodology for this study doesn’t make sense and I feel like worlds were put in my mouth.
